<p>The following materials were published in the 2011 Right Stuf boxset release of <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em>; they were produced at various dates from 1997 to 2011. Translation by Sarah Alys Lindholm (see Nozomi credits); transcribed by C.A.P November-December 2012.</p>
<section id="ikuhara-episode-commentary" class="level1">
<h1>Ikuhara episode commentary</h1>
<p>DIRECTOR KUNIHIKO IKUHARAâ€™S EPISODE COMMENTARY: PART 1</p>
<section id="the-rose-bride-episode-1" class="level2">
<h2>1: â€œTHE ROSE BRIDEâ€ [Episode 1]</h2>
<p>During the process of getting from the plan to the production deal, I needed to convey the image of the show to a lot of stakeholders in a way that would be easy to understand.</p>
<p>So I made the written plan an â€œitâ€™s something like thisâ€ type of thing. And in fact, it got the gist across, and I think itâ€™s what got us a green light on the production.</p>
<p>However, when we finally entered the production stage, I was plagued with worry. Suddenly I was brooding over what the showâ€™s originality really was. Style of expression is key in a TV series. A unique individuality. A mode no one has ever seen before. There was this pressure of â€œI have to make this a show with a special type of visual expression. Thatâ€™s the only way people will want it.â€</p>
<p>I decided to use â€œAbsolute Destiny Apocalypse.â€ And that prompted a switch to flip in my mind. Within myself, I could sense that this would be a special show. But, it was hard to explain that â€œspecialnessâ€ to the public during pre-production.</p>
<p>I talked about the story. I explained the characters. But no matter how bombastic I was, nobody understood me past the level of: â€œIt sounds like an eccentric show.â€ So all throughput pre-production, I had these pangs of guilt, like I was deceiving someone.</p>
<p>And then.</p>
<p>The first episode was given sound at last. It was complete.</p>
<p>The impression of the first stakeholder to watch it was something along the lines of â€œHuh? What is this?â€</p>
</section>
<section id="for-whom-the-rose-smiles-episode-2" class="level2">
<h2>2: â€œFOR WHOM THE ROSE SMILESâ€ [Episode 2]</h2>
<blockquote>
<p>â€œThe bird fights its way out of the egg. The egg is the world. Who would be born must first destroy a world. The bird flies to God. That Godâ€™s name is Abraxas.â€</p>
<p>â€“Hermann Hesse, <em>Demian</em> (translated from the German by Michael Roloff and Michael Lebeck)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>When I was in middle school, my classmate T. recommended to me a book by Hesse.</p>
<p>He said, â€œInside the book is everything about me.â€ I didnâ€™t know what he was on about.</p>
<p>However, that particular quote stuck with me. One day long afterwards, T. and I met up again after not seeing each other for over a decade, and I brought it up.</p>
<p>â€œWhat was that, again?â€</p>
<p>He didnâ€™t even remember the book existed, let alone that heâ€™d recommended it to me. To think heâ€™d just forget â€œeverything about himselfâ€â€¦ I wonder if Hesse wasnâ€™t needed in the world T. lived in after middle school. In which case, I wonder why I didnâ€™t forget. I experimentally added another passage to Hesseâ€™s:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><em>If we donâ€™t crack the worldâ€™s shell, we will die without being born.</em></p>
<p><em>Smash the worldâ€™s shell. For the revolution of the world.</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p>Assistant Director Kaneko [Shingo] and I discussed Anthyâ€™s character time and again because I was obsessed with the idea that whether or not it was â€œgoodâ€, nobody would want to watch a dark and depressing show. That cooking smock over gym clothes was the result of our conversations. And she finally turned funâ€¦no, she turned into a mysterious girl (!).</p>
<p><em>Anthy is another Utena.</em> In the initial stages of planning, I thought of the main character as someone who wants to be a prince, but at the same time also wanted to remain a princess. However, I decided to divide that personality into two different characters. What did â€œalso want to remain a princessâ€ mean? I would agonize over the expression of Anthy for the entire series.</p>
</section>
<section id="on-the-night-of-the-ball-episode-3" class="level2">
<h2>3: â€œON THE NIGHT OF THE BALLâ€ [Episode 3]</h2>
<p>The basic plot of this episode was ready quite soon after planning started. I believe the thinking was, â€œWe need to bring the mood of Ms. [Chiho] Saitoâ€™s manga into this.â€ But the truth is, you donâ€™t see clichÃ©d plotlines like this in Ms.Â Saitoâ€™s manga. The way Touga [Kiryuu] approaches Utena is almost uncomfortably stereotypical shoujo, but thanks to that, we were able to strongly impress upon the audience that this was a â€œshoujo manga anime.â€ Given the storyâ€™s later development, episodes like this were absolutely necessary.</p>
<p>Production-wise, we were in disorder. In the background art meeting, we discover that the master layout drawing (the base sketches for the backgrounds) that were supposed to have been ready were more or less nonexistent. As the ashen-faced staff looked on, Mr.Â Kobayashi and I sketched like mad. It was an ordeal, but I think that, over the course of dealing with it, the two of us were able to achieve a consensus about the direction the art should take for the rest of the series.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-sunlit-garden---prelude-episode-4" class="level2">
<h2>4: â€œTHE SUNLIT GARDEN - PRELUDEâ€ [Episode 4]</h2>
<p>â€œThe Sunlit Gardenâ€ is a song about the world you can never get back; the nostalgic world you can never return to again. Its true meaning will become clear during the climax of the series.</p>
<p>I made such a radical departure in the second half of this that you might as well ask yourself, â€œIs this the same show?â€ I did it to solidify the positions of Nanamiâ€™s and Anthyâ€™s characters, but by the storyboarding stage, Anthy was becoming even more of a mysterious girl (!). Meanwhile, Nanami [Kiryuu] became more of an entertaining girl.</p>
<p>Is that all right? Sure itâ€™s all right.</p>
<p>I decided to operate according to the rule â€œNever give a character only one personality.â€ I didnâ€™t want to reject â€œfunâ€ on the grounds of â€œI canâ€™t get this character to be uniformly consistent.â€</p>
</section>
<section id="the-sunlit-garden---finale-episode-5" class="level2">
<h2>5: â€œTHE SUNLIT GARDEN - FINALEâ€ [EPISODE 5]</h2>
<p>Around that time in production, I read an interview with a certain pair of pop idols in a magazine I was thumbing through at the store.</p>
<p>â€œOur motto is â€˜get hold of eternity.â€™ Itâ€™s a brilliantly glittering thing.â€</p>
<p>I was a little surprised.</p>
<p>â€œGet hold of eternityâ€ was such an abstract phrase, and yet for some reason, I readily accepted it. It was as if from that single phrase I could indirectly sense the details that shaped their personalities; the look of the place where they grew up; what they saw of current affairs on the TV news; the manga, anime, and popular songs that affected them. Call it the empathy between contemporaries, I guess.</p>
<p>When I brought it up with Enokido, who was doing the screenplays, he was onboard. Up until that point, weâ€™d spent a lot of time arguing in the abstract about the spirit of the show, but I felt like it was a few words from these pop idols that got us to the heart of the matter.</p>
<p>At the same time, the process of producing this two-parter set of episodes brought home to me again that <em>Utena</em> is a story about the relationship between characters. When you get right down to it, this series is a story about the relationship between Utena and Anthy. So I decided to apply that same style to the stories of the supporting characters, too.</p>
<p>From then on, I would be very conscious of â€œget hold of eternityâ€ and â€œa story about relationshipsâ€ as key motifs of the show.</p>
</section>
<section id="take-care-miss-nanami-episode-6" class="level2">
<h2>6: â€œTAKE CARE, MISS NANAMI!â€ [EPISODE 6]</h2>
<p>This episode originally went into production as â€œEpisode 8.â€ It was â€œin production as Episode 8â€ during scripting, storyboarding, and even after animation started. But it got switched in the broadcast order with â€œEpisode 6 (â€Curried High Tripâ€œ, which broadcast as episode 8)â€, because that episode fell behind schedule.</p>
<p>Because I always called this â€œEpisode 8â€ during the production process, the impression stuck in my mind to this day is: â€œCurry is Ep 6; the kangaroo is Ep 8.â€</p>
<p>Itâ€™s a comedic story, but it shows Nanamiâ€™s feelings for Touga. This wasnâ€™t just about Nanami; it was also about how weâ€™d present Touga. The original plan was to connect stories with a â€œTouga Episodesâ€ theme: first in episode 8 weâ€™d show Nanamiâ€™s feelings for Touga is a comedic way, then in episode 9 weâ€™d show Touga in contrast with [Kyouichi] Saionji, then in episode 10 weâ€™d show Touga using Nanamiâ€™s feeling for him, and finally in episode 11 weâ€™d show Touga facing off against Utena.</p>
<p>Iâ€™d used a group of three identical characters before, in <em>Sailor Moon S</em>. It was strangely fun, so I tried sticking them in this show, too. The staff liked them, too (it was probably more like the staff found them convenient), so we turned them into semi-regular characters. Itâ€™s largely thanks to Ms.Â Hayashi, the animation director, that the production troubles werenâ€™t reflected in the quality of the episode. I like how Touga looks so unnecessarily cool during the climax, when he defeats the kangaroo.</p>
</section>
<section id="unfulfilled-jury-episode-7" class="level2">
<h2>7: â€œUNFULFILLED JURYâ€ [EPISODE 7]</h2>
<p>This story came together quickly as a â€œstory about relationships.â€ â€œHeâ€ and â€œsheâ€ only appear within Juryâ€™s memories. The ending in the final script is different than it was in the first draft. The endgame is still about getting a better idea of who Jury really is; that didnâ€™t change. But the first draft ended on a â€œCould it be?â€ sort of a note. As the script was finalized, I decided to come right out and say, â€œShe was in love with a girl.â€</p>
<p>Juryâ€™s story is â€œa metaphor of unrequited love.â€ If you watch it from that perspective, I think itâ€™s an easy one for anybody to understand. Shioriâ€™s design referenced the heroine of Ms.Â Saitoâ€™s short manga <em>Himegoto no Natsu</em>. Itâ€™s about a brother and sister entering a forbidden relationship; I enjoyed the total mismatch between the heroineâ€™s sweet prettiness and the storyâ€™s bold development. I think we borrowed her looks because we wanted to hide something behind prettiness.</p>
</section>
<section id="curried-high-trip-episode-8" class="level2">
<h2>8: â€œCURRIED HIGH TRIPâ€ [EPISODE 8]</h2>
<p>As I said before, this was planned as episode 6. Weâ€™d originally contracted an outside studio to do it, but a few days before ADR was supposed to start, it became clear that virtually none of the production was done. We hurriedly swapped it with episode 8 (broadcast episode 6) in the schedule. The whole series of knockabout insanity that got bandied back and forth there was traumatically intense.</p>
<p>I donâ€™t want to assign blame and try anyone in absentia here, so I wonâ€™t say any more about it.</p>
<p>But if you were to ask me whether I hate the episode because of that fuss, Iâ€™d say no, not really. In fact, there are many parts of it that Iâ€™m quite fond of. I think the colossal effort the staff put in with their backs against the wall like that sublimated the episodeâ€™s cheapness into solid humor.</p>
<p>That scene when our heroinesâ€™ daily lives with their switched personalities are stung together with snapshotsâ€¦ Iâ€™ve thought for a long time that the audio mix was kind of thin there, but in this 5.1 remaster, itâ€™s finally got nice, lively sound.</p>
<p>Which reminds me: What had me worried during production was this episodeâ€™s â€œclimax.â€</p>
<p>â€œWhich scene is the climactic one?!â€, I agonized.</p>
<p>Looking back on it now, maybe it was the part when Nanami slipped on the banana peel?</p>
<p>[And then, for Ep 9-12, Ikuhara begins to take a more philosophic turn to his commentsâ€¦ â€“C.A.P.]</p>
</section>
<section id="the-castle-said-to-hold-eternity-episode-9" class="level2">
<h2>9: â€œTHE CASTLE SAID TO HOLD ETERNITYâ€ [EPISODE 9]</h2>
<p>â€œThere was a little princess, and she was very sad for her mother and father had diedâ€¦â€</p>
<p>Thatâ€™s a fragment of the myth that we tell in the prologue.</p>
<p>â€œLiving onâ€¦ Itâ€™s just making me sick.â€</p>
<p>We lined up plot development and visuals suggestive of the series climax. Our goal was to â€œget viewers anticipating the seriesâ€™ final scene.â€</p>
<p>Utena saves Anthy.<br/>Huh, so thatâ€™s what the storyâ€™s about.<br/>But what does she saves Anthy <em>from</em>?<br/>Thatâ€™s the central issue.</p>
<p>Two boys discovered an <em>unusual</em> toy one day.<br/>â€œYou got hold of it, didnâ€™t you?â€<br/>â€œThatâ€™s right, I have it now.â€<br/>â€œReally?â€</p>
<p>Thatâ€™s when the game began.</p>
<p>It often happens that a relationship becomes stifling because of a shared past. Even if you have no particular interest in a toy, when you find out <em>he</em> has it, you think, â€œI need it too.â€</p>
<p>They say that in <em>that world</em>, only one princess is chosen.</p>
</section>
<section id="nanamis-precious-thing-episode-10" class="level2">
<h2>10: â€œNANAMIâ€™S PRECIOUS THINGâ€ [EPISODE 10]</h2>
<p>When I was a child, the center of the party always seemed to sparkle.</p>
<p>I was always standing on the sidelines, gazing at that sparkle from afar. I thought the sidelines were my place. Surely I could never approach the center of the room.</p>
<p>But then, I was chosen! I touched that sparkle in the center of the room, and no mistake. Still, I know full well that itâ€™s something that wonâ€™t last forever. The day the contract ends, Iâ€™ll turn into an â€œunchosen girl.â€</p>
<p>So Iâ€™ll go back to the sidelines again, eh?</p>
<p>â€“Smash the eggâ€™s shell.</p>
<p>For the revolution of the world.</p>
</section>
<section id="gracefully-cruel---the-one-who-picks-that-flower-episode-11" class="level2">
<h2>11: â€œGRACEFULLY CRUEL - THE ONE WHO PICKS THAT FLOWERâ€ [EPISODE 11]</h2>
<p>I tried to live true to myself.</p>
<p>â€œYouâ€™re just like an alienâ€, someone said to me one day. They must have been telling me, â€œYouâ€™re not normal.â€</p>
<p>In other words, apparently â€œliving true to yourselfâ€ means â€œliving as an alien.â€ And so I became â€œan alien all alone in this world.â€</p>
<p>Thereâ€™s a certain natural law that goes, â€œTo gain something, you must lose something.â€ Thereâ€™s nobody in this world who gains everything. Otherwise, there would be people who could live forever.</p>
<p><em>That</em> is something she is blind to.</p>
<p>Thatâ€™s why she loses whatâ€™s important to her.</p>
<p>Why did she want to become a prince?<br/>Who was it who wanted to become a princess?<br/>Do <em>you</em> want to be chosen by someone, too?<br/>Orâ€“?</p>
</section>
<section id="for-friendship-perhaps-episode-12" class="level2">
<h2>12: â€œFOR FRIENDSHIP, PERHAPSâ€ [EPISODE 12]</h2>
<p>Why did I join that battle (that game) in the first place?<br/>Naturally, I would never forget that.<br/>And yet.<br/>Thereâ€™s no sense of reality to that memory.</p>
<p>Who was I, exactly?</p>
<p>â€œIâ€™m saying this for your sake.â€ How many times did I hear that as a child?</p>
<p>An â€œadultâ€ is not someone who has lived a certain number of years. We call someone who can exercise power an â€œadult.â€</p>
