<section id="rondo-revolution-kunihiko-ikuharas-thoughts" class="level1">
<h1>Rondo Revolution: Kunihiko Ikuharaâ€™s Thoughts</h1>
<p>There were several forks in the road to the theme song â€œRondo - revolutionâ€.</p>
<p>First I had X, the producer at the time, play me several demo melodies. One of them really felt like â€œthe oneâ€, so I decided on that one with X (naturally, the chosen one was the melody that would become â€œRondo - revolutionâ€, but we also released it separately later in a form close to that original one, under the title â€œRose&amp;releaseâ€).</p>
<p>Next, X set up a meeting for us with a certain lyricist at a restaurant in Shibuya. We explained the project, presenting Ms.Â Saitoâ€™s drawings, and the lyricist seemed really raring to go.</p>
<p>But.</p>
<p>The lyrics that came back to us some days later didnâ€™t sit well with me.</p>
<p>â€œTheyâ€™re just not quite rightâ€¦â€ X agreed, and fell silent.</p>
<p>Several days later, I got a phone call from X saying, â€œShe says she wants to do it. Iâ€™ll have her call you, so stay put.â€ This phone call was how I found out that Ms.Â Okui would be singing the theme song. And that she would be singing the theme song. And that she would take charge of the lyrics herself, too. Right after X hung up, I got a phone call from Ms.Â Okui, and we ended up having a meeting.</p>
<p>Iâ€™ll dredge up my memories of that time period to write the rest of this story. This all happened a long time ago, though, so there will be some details I canâ€™t remember.</p>
<p>I got a phone call from Ms.Â Okui.</p>
<p>We started our planning meeting on the spot, but production was still ongoing, for one thing, so in terms of the showâ€™s contentâ€¦ I couldnâ€™t tell her a lot of crucial things. Nevertheless, sheâ€™d thankfully read several of Ms.Â Saitoâ€™s works, so she already understood the â€œspirit of the workâ€ very well.</p>
<p>That meant that in our meeting, we were able to focus on â€œwhat weâ€™re trying to expressâ€ instead of on the story. By their very natures, thereâ€™s no way to perfectly reconcile â€œthe world of songâ€ and â€œthe world of anime stories.â€ But I felt there ought to be a way to bring together the spirits of â€œsongâ€ and â€œanime.â€</p>
<p><strong>â€œI want you to think of this as a song that will play during the storyâ€™s last scene.â€</strong></p>
<p>Thatâ€™s what I told her. Like I said, we hadnâ€™t decided what the last scene would be yet. Still, I had a vague suspicion that it would depict a â€œparting.â€ At the time I didnâ€™t have a concrete image of what kind it might be; thereâ€™s-</p>
<p><strong>parting with a lover,</strong><br/><strong>parting with a dear friend,</strong><br/><strong>parting with a beloved sibling or</strong><br/><strong>family member,</strong><br/><strong>parting with the entire milieu in which</strong><br/><strong>you liveâ€¦</strong></p>
<p>Those were my nebulous thoughts.</p>
<p>What could a person whoâ€™d lost all those things gain in the final sceneâ€¦? It would be magnificent if that could be captured to a songâ€¦ Surely the viewers who watched the series through the end would think, â€œI see, so the theme song was about this final sceneâ€ â€¦</p>
<p>Some days later, I faxed her a note.</p>
<p><strong>Even if the two of us are torn apart,</strong><br/><strong>the time that we spent together</strong><br/><strong>wasnâ€™t wasted</strong><br/><strong>So I can change the world</strong></p>
<p>I asked her if she could express something along those lines. And I also had the temerity to ask her to include a few keywords in the lyrics that expressed the world of the show:</p>
<p>â€œsunlit gardenâ€<br/>â€œrevolutionizeâ€<br/>â€œlose everythingâ€<br/>â€œstrip down to nothing at allâ€<br/>â€œchange the worldâ€</p>
<p>Several days after that, the finished lyrics were faxed back to me. My â€œgardenâ€ and â€œrevolutionâ€ suggestions in Japanese were there in English. I thought the showâ€™s spirit was expressed brilliantly.</p>
<p>Above the lyrics was a note saying, â€œWhat should the title be?â€ (I think). I also think that â€œTake my revolutionâ€ was there as a provisional title. And in another display of temerity, I asked if sheâ€™d be willing to write the kanji for <em>rinbu</em> (â€œround danceâ€) but gloss it as â€œrondoâ€ to arrive at a title of â€œrondorevolution.â€ She agreed, on the condition that we inset a hyphen and make it â€œRondo - revolution.â€ (Or maybe the changes went like this: â€œRondo - Take my revolutionâ€ â†’ â€œRondorevolu - tionâ€ â†’ â€œRondo - revolutionâ€.) I took my inspiration from Ms.Â Saitoâ€™s manga for the word â€œrondo.â€</p>
<p>Later, even when production circumstances were harsh, this song really bolstered my spirits. This is only occurring to me in hindsight, but maybe it was able to express the â€œUtenaâ€ spirit so well because Ms.Â Okui and I were in very similar frames of mind at the time</p>
