<section id="the-sunlit-garden---Ã©tude" class="level2">
<h2>The Sunlit Garden - Ã‰tude</h2>
<p><strong>Series Structure Yoji Enokido â€“ [BE-PAPAS]</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>So what is this showâ€™s scenario driving at?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Aw, come on, donâ€™t ask me that. Iâ€™ll blush. The cage may be one that you can slip out of one day without even knowing. However, the moment comes when, quite by chance, you notice the existence of that â€œlabyrinth.â€ There comes a time when you realize youâ€™ve lost sight of the path you must take, and now youâ€™re lost. Maybe itâ€™s when you happen to visit an old building, and you see the light filtering in through its skylight. Or maybe itâ€™s when you hear a cicada chirping in the woods one summer at dusk. There comes a time when you feel something the word â€œnostalgiaâ€ alone canâ€™t encompass; something heartrending that you feel throughout your whole body. â€œAh, thatâ€™s right, I remember this sensation. Itâ€™s nice, isnâ€™t itâ€¦â€ Itâ€™s not like you want to board a time machine and go back to your past, but you do long to savor past pleasures one more time, to experience them vicariously. No, thatâ€™s not right. What I want to say here isnâ€™t that there are moments when you wish for something like that; itâ€™s that the yearning to vicariously re-experience those times from your past is present in all humans on a fundamental level. That there are moments when you become aware of that fact. Our philosophy of love, our ideal of the future - I wonder if those things arenâ€™t largely rooted in that â€œyearning for vicarious experienceâ€; if that yearning isnâ€™t another factor besides the genetic information coded into us from birth. Setting aside the question of whether thatâ€™s most properly called a learned motive, a desire for the sense of omnipotence we once had, or something we can write off more simply with the word â€œsentiment,â€ the point is that there comes a time when itâ€™s brought home to you that the â€œyearning for vicarious experienceâ€ is something you have within your own heart as well - a force almost like gravity. â€œThe same tone as my little sisterâ€™sâ€¦â€ Miki blurts in a whisper. â€œThat sunlit gardenâ€¦ Iâ€™ve found it. My â€˜shining thing.â€™â€ And we instinctively know that itâ€™s dangerous. Thereâ€™s nothing inherently wrong with sentimentality, of course. Sentimentality is a tool that can, and should, be used. However, because humans are fundamentally beings which live into the future, if we are ruled by sentiment, we lose the momentum to keep flowing forward and become stagnant. Thatâ€™s why we this a â€œlabyrinth.â€ By the way, labyrinths are symbols of growth and death. After being hurt emotionally, people often set off on journeys into a labyrinth-esque device. The labyrinth of the mind has no physical form, so itâ€™s hard to grasp with the senses. And so you â€œsolveâ€ the problem by synchronizing your mental labyrinth with a visible one: you wander across a physical distance or through a physical course, and if your wound heals youâ€™ve reached the center. But when a man arrives at the center of a labyrinth, he is no longer the man he was before he entered. Growth means the death of the person you were up until that point. The labyrinth called â€œlifeâ€ has no physical form, either. Out â€œway of life,â€ known as â€œcreation,â€ can perhaps be thought of as the formalization of the unseen into the easily understood.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>So what is it you want to portray, exactly?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Mikiâ€™s lament of â€œWhy canâ€™t I find someone to be my â€˜shining thingâ€™?â€ Miki Kaoruâ€™s â€œshining thingâ€ symbolizes the desire for vicarious experience, of course. The white house on the hill, the greener grass on the other side the hill, and the castle in the sky. Itâ€™s not just limited to the desire for vicarious experience - the motif of â€œthe happiness on the other sideâ€ comes up over and over again in <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em>. For some reason, we almost never depict a â€œsampleâ€ of happiness itself. Even the â€œUtenaâ€ in the title isnâ€™t the flower itself: itâ€™s the calyx<a href="#fn5" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref5"><sup>5</sup></a> on which the flower rests.</p>
<p>The â€œshining thingâ€, the desire to vicariously re-experience times past. I donâ€™t wish to gainsay that. (That sunlit garden is too beautiful for me to gainsay it all.) I donâ€™t wish to merely show off its beauty either, though. (If youâ€™re simply ruled by sentimentality, you canâ€™t even maintain the capacity to truly experience beauty.) Perhaps all Iâ€™ve really done here is to briefly point out the theme within the story of â€œThe Sunlit Gardenâ€, and this whole piece of writing has been nothing but an Ã©tude Iâ€™m playing in preparation for a story I have yet to write. The sight of someone who is aware that he is being ruled by sentimentality toward the past even as it is ruling him, and who in time matures into effectively wielding such sentiment as a tool in his arsenal, and the framework of this world, which is set up to let that happen - Iâ€™m sure thatâ€™s what I want to portray. Itâ€™s what I feel I should portray. The fact that weâ€™re loved by the world. The fact that that we can still love the world. Because when you get right down to it, I think what I ought to convey through this form called screenwriting is a love letter. (Actually, I think all creative works should be love letters.) And the â€œmost important thingâ€ about a love letter isnâ€™t its style of expression, so we mustnâ€™t commit the folly of striving for technical superiority to the exclusion of all else. (Technique alone wonâ€™t make you eloquent. You need passion! Passion!) Not that anybody ever kindly tells me â€œYour lack of perfection is your strength.â€ (laughs)</p>
</section>
<section id="the-shape-of-the-job" class="level2">
<h2>The Shape Of The Job</h2>
<p><strong>Character Design<br/>Shinya Hasegawa â€“ [BE-PAPAS]</strong></p>
<p>As Iâ€™m writing this, there are only two months left on the production of <em>Utena</em>.</p>
<p>Weâ€™re running out of money fast, so youâ€™d think Iâ€™d operating at peak voltage, but Iâ€™m actually awfully composed; in fact, in my ninth year as an animator Iâ€™m working more calmly than I ever have before.</p>
<p>Back in the day, I felt a sense of exhilaration and accomplishment at each new thing, under each set of circumstances: when my name first appeared on television as an in-between animator, when I learned key animation techniques by example, when I took part in a video or theatrical project, and then when I became an â€œAnimation Directorâ€, when my illustrations were published in magazines or productsâ€¦ But that lasted only about three years. After youâ€™ve more or less experienced all the stages, you can better imagine the future. In due course you come to see what you couldnâ€™t see before. I felt my interests (or motivations) shift based on trends going on around me, my own position, and closely fought battles there.</p>
<p>In terms of my character design job for <em>Utena</em>, I didnâ€™t have much interest in the results themselves.</p>
<p>The issue is what shall I make the designs like, can I make them, what should I do in order to make them, how do I use them effectively once theyâ€™re madeâ€¦? Itâ€™s boring if youâ€™re just sitting there making them and thatâ€™s all. What Iâ€™m after isnâ€™t the colored celluloid film or the print; itâ€™s the process associated with those things.</p>
<p>As an analogy, sakÃ¨ is nothing but a potent fuel to propel you to the result of getting drunk and making a scene, but itâ€™s only when you drink it calmly and with self-control that you can first sense the â€œdepthâ€ of sakÃ¨ that encompasses its subtle flavor, its aroma, and the process of its production.</p>
<p>I donâ€™t really have any intention of going on about the final results; Iâ€™m sure Iâ€™d just end up grumbling, and at myself not least of all. I donâ€™t let feelings that things didnâ€™t go as well as I wanted turn into pessimism; theyâ€™re my driving force for my next go-round.</p>
<p>I might not be able to get the results I want for a while, but I think thatâ€™s just fine.</p>
<p>Because when I reach that point, itâ€™ll all be over.</p>
