<h2>Deliberate Mismatches</h2>
<p><strong>Planning<br/>Yuichirou Oguro â€“ [BE-PAPAS]</strong></p>
<p>BE-PAPAS is a planning and story conception group that Kunihiko Ikuhara brought together to create <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em>. Itâ€™s made up of five people: leader Kunihiko Ikuhara, Chiho Saito, Yoji Enokido, Shinya Hasegawa, and me, Yuichirou Oguro.</p>
<p>Right now Iâ€™d like to talk about the planning of this show as well as its distinctive flavor.</p>
<p>The basic concept of <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em> is â€œa romantic action show starring a pretty girl who wears boysâ€™ clothes.â€ Thereâ€™s also the element of â€œTakarazuka style.â€</p>
<p><em>Revolutionary Girl Utenaâ€™</em>s planning began when Director Ikuhara saw an illustration by Ms.Â Saito in a book store and fell in love at first sight. Wouldnâ€™t a pretty-girl action show that made the most of Ms.Â Saitoâ€™s romantic quality as a manga artist be interesting? Director Ikuhara and I immediately asked Ms.Â Chiho for her cooperation in planning the project.</p>
<p>To show off the brilliant mood of Ms.Â Saitoâ€™s manga to its greatest advantage, the main character become â€œa pretty girl who dresses as a boy.â€ The decision to make it a â€œschool showâ€ was settled early on, too. Ideas like the â€œRose Brideâ€ and the â€œduelsâ€ came much later.</p>
<p>After Ms.Â Saito joined us, the plans kind of fluctuated - okay, more like jolted back and forth enough to give a man whiplash - for a while, and then the story and setup were largely settled. In other words, the planning was finished.</p>
<p>Ms.Â Saitoâ€™s manga serialization started up, the TV broadcast deal was closed, and the real production work started at last.</p>
<p>During the planning stage, Director Ikuhara had devoted his passion to finding the best way to bring the world of Chiho Saitoâ€™s work to life in anime form, but at this point he started really adding his own flavor to the show. The stage-like layout, the shadow girls, J.A. Caesarâ€™s choral songs, and all the rest. With the injection of this Ikuhara flavor, the show further expanded in leaps and bounds.</p>
<p>Now that the manga and anime have been both started up, Ms.Â Saito has been pulling <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em> in a more romantic direction, and Director Ikuhara has been pulling it in the direction of his own tastes. And even as he aids both of them in their tug-of-war, Yoji Enokido incorporates his tastes as well. Itâ€™s fair to say that the basic flavor of <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em> is formed from the individual personalities of those three people: Ikuhara, Saito, and Enokido.</p>
<p>The interesting thing is that Kunihiko Ikuhara is both â€œoriginal creatorâ€ and â€œdirector.â€</p>
<p>In other words, he planned <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em> as a â€œTakarazuka-style romantic storyâ€, and now that production has started up, heâ€™s taken that â€œTakarazuka-style romantic storyâ€ as the base text, directed it, and steadily fleshed out the show.</p>
<p>Around the time we started planning <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em>, he and I had a conversation about how perhaps the most interesting works had â€œan element of mismatch, but in a good way.â€ If itâ€™s a mismatch for Ms.Â Saito to draw a pretty-girl action piece with eccentric costuming, itâ€™s certainly also a mismatch for Director Ikuhara to direct a â€œChiho Saito romantic action piece.â€</p>
<p>Weâ€™re doing that on purpose.</p>
<p>In <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em>, Director Ikuhara deliberately set up a twofold mismatch and then made a success out of it. Itâ€™s the kind of elaborate strategy youâ€™d expect from the villain of a full-blown detective novel.</p>
<p>That twofold mismatch is what produces the <em>Revolutionary Girl Utena</em> animeâ€™s mysterious flavor.</p>
