<p><code>O</code>: Director Ikuhara tells me he agonized over that as well - but I believe he found something in your songs that would let them over come those obstacles. He says, â€œRight now Iâ€™m the only one who can use Caesarâ€™s songs, and I think this is the perfect chance to unleash his songs on our present era. Iâ€™m placing a bet here. I want to create the work this way in order to create something new, something you might call experimental anime.â€ Please, I entreat you to support us.</p>
<p>I close my eyes - I was sensing now the same â€œoverthrowing of myselfâ€ that Iâ€™d sensed when I met <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shuji%20Terayama" title="Wikipedia: Shuji Terayama">Shuji Terayama</a>. <em>A record of somewhere, a technique into the past.</em> A means of trying to set a trap of imaginative power directed at a society ruled by unavoidable inevitability and locked in conflict with inexorability. A gamblerâ€™s dramaturgy. And above all else, a dramatization with an aleatory structureâ€¦ Wagner and Ludwig IIâ€¦ Wagner and Nietzscheâ€¦ Once upon a time, in a place far, far, away, there lived meâ€¦ a strategy of new intellectâ€¦ revolutionâ€¦ <em>U-ten-a</em>â€¦</p>
<p>They say that music thatâ€™s left the nest to stand on its own two feet shall meet many new friends, heal more than one heart, uplift, and sometimes even become a living human being. It was in my apartment late that night that I realized this was equivalent to the meaning of â€œanimateâ€, the root of the world â€œanimation.â€ <em>Animate: to breathe life into, to invigorate. to uplift. lively. vivid. briskâ€¦</em></p>
